title: For Sale:  Stoeger (Beretta) Cougar 8045F
postcontent: I'm selling my pristine compact .45 Cal Stoeger (Beretta) Cougar 8045 like new w/case/box, 2 8-round magazines and 50 rounds of ammo. When Beretta stopped making their own Cougar 8000 handguns in 9mm, .40 Cal and .45 Cal they moved the factory (tooling and everything) to their Stoeger facility in Turkey and continued making them there.  Labor costs dropped considerably, but the Beretta quality remains and these really nice handguns are a steal at their MSRP. This .45 is an amazing weapon and very comfortable to shoot and pin point accurate. This is the third Stoeger Cougar that I've had (2 9mm and this .45) and I'll put them up against any handgun on the market for value, reliability, accuracy, build quality and durability. Besides that it's a fine looking weapon. They are DA/SA with a decocker lever on the rear of the slide (a la typical Beretta pistols). This .45 even has an accessory rail, which is not found on the 9mm or the .40 Cal. A really nice handgun at a bargan price. Local pickup/exchange means NO tax, NO shipping fee, NO ffl transfer fee, NO federal forms to fill out and NO waiting.

postcontent: US M1 Garand Rifle; October, 1941 Production/British Issue; .30-06. Pre-war production Lend/Lease M1 Garand Rifle. This is an excellent example of, original condition 1941 M1. Manufactured at the Springfield Armory. The rifle was one of a number shipped as military aid to the United Kingdom under the Lend-Lease Act. The rifle is identified by its low serial number, matching, pre-war date(10-41), and British proof marks on the barrel. All parts appear original and correct for the time of production. In excellent, apparently unissued condition. Original arsenal phosphate finish is better than 95% with the gas cylinder expectedly turned a silvery pewter. There is the occasional rub mark typical of parkerization, as well as traces of old, dried grease, but no rust, pitting or fading of finish are visible on any component other than the gas cylinder. Markings are well-struck, correct, and include the BNP/Tonnage markings and Birmingham House Proofs. There is no import or export mark on the rifle, and the barrel date, 10-41, corresponds with the serial number. All marked components are of Springfield make, with the trigger guard housing and safety possibly being replacements. Furniture rates as near excellent as refinished, with an added coat of lacquer. There are two superficial hairline cracks eminating from the upper rear handguard and no other visible chips, repairs or damage, apart from light handling marks and the occassional pressure dent. There is a faded circle-P firing proof on the pistol grip, as well as a faded Ordnance Wheel and "SA-GHS" cartouche on the left of the stock, and the furniture is correct for the gun and almost certainly original.
